<DESCRIPT>  OAKLAND; BERKELEY; MOUNTAIN; FIRE; CHARITY; AID; LIST  </DESCRIPT>
<LEADPARA>  (box) Finding people: To locate close relatives in shelters, call the Oakland
Red Cross at (510) 535-2840. The Red Cross is asking that only those with a
real need call this line.; (box) Homes: Those evacuated may find out when they
can return to their homes by calling two special Oakland Fire Department
lines: (510) 287-6021 and (510) 287-6000.  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Front  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  HOW TO GET OR GIVE HELP  </HEADLINE>
<MEMO>  The Oakland Hills Fire; See also related stories on pages 1A and 14-20A of
this section.  </MEMO>
<TEXT>  (box) Hot lines: For general help, the Red Cross can be reached at (510)
535-2883; Students, families and employees of University of California,
Berkeley can call (510) 642-4335; Kaiser Permanente employees can call (510)
987-4672.; (box) Health: For 24-hour information on smoke inhalation and other
health problems that may have been caused by the fire, call Alta Bates
Hospital, Ask a Nurse (800) 322-1322.; (box) Shelters: In Oakland, the
shelters are at Oakland Technical High School, 4351 Broadway, and King Estates
Junior High School, 8251 Fontaine St. In Berkeley, they are at Willard Junior
High School, 2425 Stuart St.; and the UC-Berkeley student union.; (box)
Temporary housing: Eden I&amp;R Inc. of Hayward, a non-profit corporation, will
try to match fire victims with those who can provide housing. Those who need
housing can call (510) 537-2552; those who can supply housing can call (510)
537-2710. Collect calls will be accepted from 9 a.m. to 5 p.m.; (box) Schools:
All 12 Oakland public schools that were closed Monday will remain closed
today. All but Hillcrest and Kaiser elementary schools will open Wednesday.
Orinda public schools and all Berkeley public schools, except possibly John
Muir School near the Claremont Hotel, will be open today. To find out if John
Muir will open today, call (510) 644-6320 after 6 a.m. UC-Berkeley classes
also resume today. The California College of Arts and Crafts will reopen
Wednesday.; (box) Transportation: A six-mile stretch of Highway 13, connecting
Highway 24 with Interstate 580 in Oakland, is closed indefinitely. Highway 24
and the BART track along the Caldecott Tunnel reopened Monday, as well as the
BART tracks between the Rockridge and Orinda stations. BART can be reached at
(510) 465-BART.; (box) Insurance: Fire victims wanting help with fire
insurance claims may call the toll-free state Department of Insurance hot line
at (800) 927-HELP. Veterans with Cal-Vet homes may call (800) 626-1613
toll-free.; (box) Mental health: For help with fire-related anxiety or grief,
call Alameda County's 24-hour crisis intervention line at (510) 849-2212.;
(box) Mail: Anyone who wants to receive mail addressed to areas that have been
devastated can call (510) 874-8200 after 8:30 a.m.; (box) Phones: Pacific Bell
is offering free services to evacuees. For voice-mail service, call toll-free
(800) 427-7715, ext. 345. For call-forwarding service, call a Pacific Bell
business office.; (box) Furniture: Cort Furniture Rental Corp. will provide
one month's free furniture rental for fire victims. Cort has showrooms in San
Francisco, South San Francisco, Mountain View and Santa Clara.; (box)
Rebuilding: The California Department of Housing and the city of Oakland have
established a toll-free telephone number, (800) 552-5479, to provide
information for victims who want to repair or rebuild their homes.; (box)
Banking: Wells Fargo Bank customers who are fire victims are eligible for
unsecured loans, deferred payments on loans and extended emergency credit on
credit cards. For information on loans, call (800) 225-1778. For credit card
information, call (800) 642-4720.; (box) Payment relief: First Interstate Bank
is offering customers loan payment relief and allowing them to redeem
certificates of deposit without early withdrawal penalties.; (box) Pets: For
emergency boarding for displaced or lost pets, call the Marin Humane Society,
(415) 883-4621, or the San Francisco Department of Animal Care and Control at
its 24-hour hot line, (415) 554-9400. Volunteers at Pets Unlimited, at (415)
563-6700, also are available to help find lost pets.; (box) Volunteers: The
Salvation Army needs volunteers at 601 Webster St., Oakland, to help prepare
and dispatch food to firefighters and victims. In Santa Clara County, the
Volunteer Exchange at (408) 286-1126 is keeping a list of those willing to
volunteer.; (box) Donations: Clothing, bedding, non-perishable food and
bottled drinks will be accepted at all Salvation Army Thrift Stores. All Bay
Area Safeway stores are accepting non-perishable food, diapers, batteries and
emergency supplies (no clothing). Lucky stores are accepting non-perishable
food, batteries, cups, plates and utensils, flashlights, bottled water, etc.,
at their Alameda County and Contra Costa County stores. A food and bedding
drop-off center has been set up at Willard Junior High in Berkeley.; (box)
Money contributions: Donations of money to the East Bay Fire Fund may be
mailed to the United Way at 410 Bush St., San Francisco 94108; the American
Red Cross at 2111 E. 14th St., Oakland 94606 or 1550 Sutter St., San Francisco
94109; or the Salvation Army at P.O. Box 2D, San Jose, 95109. The American Red
Cross is accepting credit card donations at (510) 535-2812 or -2818. All
Northern California Lucky and Safeway stores -- and Nevada Safeway stores --
are also accepting donations for forwarding to the fire fund.  </TEXT>
